{"pdfpcFormat":2,"disableMarkdown":false,"noteFontSize":20,"pages":[{"idx":0,"label":"1","overlay":0,"note":"Welcome\n"},{"idx":1,"label":"2","overlay":0,"note":"So what dose this mean?\nLets start by explaning some words to get a better understanding.\n"},{"idx":2,"label":"2","overlay":1,"note":"Mechanization is the process of writing a formal proof using a computer assisted program, a so called proof assistant."},{"idx":3,"label":"2","overlay":2,"note":"PLS is semantics for code,\nthis is a formal representation of what the code dose,\nan informal version representation would be the code documentation."},{"idx":4,"label":"2","overlay":3,"note":"The goal of this thesis is to evaluate similarites between the proofs given in the course and thier Mechanized couterpart.\n"},{"idx":5,"label":"3","overlay":0,"note":"The course uses N&N framework from the book ...\nThis thesis mainly focuses on Chapter 1, which introduce the Language \"While\" Which is imperative and includes..."},{"idx":6,"label":"3","overlay":1,"note":"we also look at the chapter Operational Semnatics, which describes how the program executes."},{"idx":7,"label":"3","overlay":2,"note":"This includes definition of NS,\nwhich focuses on the final state of the execution, given an initial state.\n"},{"idx":8,"label":"3","overlay":3,"note":"We also have SOS,\nWhich in comparrisson focuses on how we arrived at the finalstep,\nshowing all intermidiary steps on the way, which can be more intresting at times."},{"idx":9,"label":"4","overlay":0,"note":"We will mechanize the proofs using Lean 4.\nLean uses Dependet  Type Theory, which means that we can create types that deepend on our values, an example of such a type is a vector, which contain both a Type it contains, but also a number of elements, the number of elements are not a Type as we are used to, but using dependet type theroy we can include this number in our types."},{"idx":10,"label":"4","overlay":1,"note":"In addtion to the type system being extensible we are provided with inductive types, which allows us to create constructions of exsting types, this allows us to say that is we have a Statement and a State, we can construct a Program, which we then can evaluate later."},{"idx":11,"label":"4","overlay":2,"note":"Tactics allows us to interact with the typesystem, allowing us guide lean step by step into creating the type we want, therby creating the proof we wanted."},{"idx":12,"label":"4","overlay":3,"note":"Due to Proofs being Types, if type checking succseeds then it must be the case that the proof is valid.\nImportantly Lean only verfies your statments to be true or false, It dose not care if your statment is nonsensical, much like how a false statment can imply anything, the same goes for Lean proofs,\nThe proof might be correct, but must check what the proof is proving before accepting it!"},{"idx":13,"label":"5","overlay":0,"note":"Rq1 do not read book name"},{"idx":14,"label":"5","overlay":1,"note":"Any assumptions left to the reader to findout?"},{"idx":15,"label":"6","overlay":0,"note":"The method used in my thesis is a repetative pattern of finding proofs or other formulations, and then mechanize it, and lastly comparing the mechanized version aginst the orignal text.\n\nBy doing this multiple times I'm able to build up a sample and therby find formulations from the text that translate well into Lean, and things that do not translate well."},{"idx":16,"label":"7","overlay":0,"note":"We will do our process for diffrent examples from our checklist of formulations in the book.\nFirst example being arithemtic expressions which is a syntactic definition found in the book.\nThis is used in the While Language when ever we want to arithemtic operation on numbers or variables.\nThe \"a\"s represents a Aritmetic expressions\nThe \"n\" represents a Numeral\nthe \"x\" represents a variable"},{"idx":17,"label":"7","overlay":1,"note":"When mecanizing it we can use the inductive keyword to construct this type.\n"},{"idx":18,"label":"7","overlay":2,"note":"Here we se the mapping from type being defined"},{"idx":19,"label":"7","overlay":3,"note":"and here the mapping of how it is defined."},{"idx":20,"label":"7","overlay":4,"note":"Here we can also see that they share a lot of similarites between each other,\nA minor diffrence here is that we must define the Types, whilst in the textbook they have defined every occurence of n, x, a and a few others as a fixed type.\nThis is Possible in Lean, but only  on a file by file basis which was more work then it was worth"},{"idx":21,"label":"8","overlay":0,"note":"Next  we have the definition of Variables,\nWhich is given as some String of digits and letters.\n\nAs we can see it is not very formaly defined,\nWhat dose this mean Lean?"},{"idx":22,"label":"8","overlay":1,"note":"Well we are lucky that Lean has a builtin version of what a String is,\nWe also need to add the property DecidableEQ,\nwhich tells Lean that a variable can be the same variable as anoter variable, otherwise it would be imposible to read the value of a variable after it has been assigned."},{"idx":23,"label":"9","overlay":0,"note":"Next we will show a Semantic function,\nThis describes how we can go from our Arithmetic exxpression called Aexp, to a Integer given a state."},{"idx":24,"label":"9","overlay":1,"note":"The mechanized version is a bit longer as we need to use the full name here to specify how its is used.\nHere we can see that the numeral mapping is very similar if we ignore the syntax difference.\n\nBut we can fixx this..."},{"idx":25,"label":"9","overlay":2,"note":"side by side,\nHard to argue if this would be considered equal.\n"},{"idx":26,"label":"10","overlay":0,"note":"By defining our custom notation we can remove the need of giving the full definition name every time we want to use it,\nthis bridges the gap that the textbook creates whenever it uses its own notation."},{"idx":27,"label":"11","overlay":0,"note":"Side by side using our custom notation we can see that the similarity is now very clear. there are still some syntaxx diffrences here, but the overall structure remains the same."},{"idx":28,"label":"12","overlay":0,"note":"Nexxt we have infernce rules which are given in a table for every statment in the language, and I know i have not shown you how statment look, but that is not important, as we are not trying to prove that the book is right, or worng, but rather if the forumaltions share any similarites when mechanized."},{"idx":29,"label":"12","overlay":1,"note":"Here we can see that the inference rule name is mapped over, where the big_step is another word for Natural Semantics."},{"idx":30,"label":"12","overlay":2,"note":"We also see that the conclusion of a inference rule has a good mapping to Lean."},{"idx":31,"label":"12","overlay":3,"note":"Next  we have the more complex if statment which uses side conditions to limit how the rule can be used in the derivation trees later on."},{"idx":32,"label":"12","overlay":4,"note":"The premise of the rule gets mapped as a condition to the Lean construction,"},{"idx":33,"label":"12","overlay":5,"note":"Same goes for the side condition, this means that a premise and side conditions are indistingusiable for Lean when it come to the proof, which make sense as both need to be proven for the rule to work."},{"idx":34,"label":"12","overlay":6,"note":"Lastly the conclusin has a good mapping as we saw before, for the assignment case."},{"idx":35,"label":"13","overlay":0,"note":"Before moving on the the next  item on the checklist\nIt is important to note that not evrything has a good mapping as we saw earlier with the Variable definition.\n\nHere we have the Semantic function that takes a statment and a State and evaluates using Natural semantics into a Final state if one exists, and undefined if the program dose not reach a final state.\n"},{"idx":36,"label":"13","overlay":1,"note":"This is trick to do in Lean as lean prefers total functions,\nTo  construct a partial function like we have on the right, we must disable the computable part of this functions, this basicaly means that we can not apply it to any values,\n\nThis affects a proof later on which uses the this semantic function.\nBut looking closely we can instead use the relation it self, and using thee exestential qualifer to get the same result, but keeping the computability part which is good."},{"idx":37,"label":"14","overlay":0,"note":"Whit functions and inference rules being done, we can move forward with some proofs,\nHere we have a prrof that claims that, next"},{"idx":38,"label":"14","overlay":1,"note":"a while statment is ... next"},{"idx":39,"label":"14","overlay":2,"note":"Semanticaly equvivalent to ... next"},{"idx":40,"label":"14","overlay":3,"note":"and if statment,\nHere the if statment is a 1 loop unroling of the while statment."},{"idx":41,"label":"15","overlay":0,"note":"here the eqvivalence proof is split in to, ... next"},{"idx":42,"label":"15","overlay":1,"note":"which is mapped weill in Lean,"},{"idx":43,"label":"16","overlay":0,"note":"Next we take one of them and continue,\n"},{"idx":45,"label":"16","overlay":2,"note":"two parts =\n1 from if to while,\n\n2 from while to if.\nWe look at the secound case... next"},{"idx":47,"label":"16","overlay":4,"note":"While stmt, next."},{"idx":48,"label":"16","overlay":5,"note":"As we can see the mapping still holds well,\nofcourse the Lean version is using less text to do the same steps given by the book."},{"idx":49,"label":"17","overlay":0,"note":"we then follow it futher where we use the while true rule to get subtrees which will be used later."},{"idx":50,"label":"18","overlay":0,"note":"We then use the subtrees, ... next"},{"idx":51,"label":"18","overlay":1,"note":"using the same rule given in the text and then ..."},{"idx":52,"label":"18","overlay":2,"note":"use the condition that we got before to ..."},{"idx":53,"label":"18","overlay":3,"note":"Construct the final statment we needed\n\nThe proof the continues in a similar fashion for the while false case, but instead of constructing a composition we use a axiom to create a skip statment instead."},{"idx":54,"label":"19","overlay":0,"note":"Due to the length of this proof i will not bore you with showing the reverse direction where we start from a if statment and prove it to be equal to the while statment,\n\nLets instead look on some other examples that shows some diffrences between the two."},{"idx":55,"label":"20","overlay":0,"note":"This example is from a porof trying to prove that if \na statment S terminates into s', and if the statmnet terminates into s'' (double prime) then that means that s' is equal to s'', which is trying to prove that it is determinstic for all inputs.\n"},{"idx":56,"label":"20","overlay":1,"note":"Here the case being evaluated is mapped well,"},{"idx":57,"label":"20","overlay":2,"note":"so is the assumption that this statement holds beacuse .."},{"idx":58,"label":"20","overlay":3,"note":"the condition is true and ..."},{"idx":59,"label":"20","overlay":4,"note":"the statement S1 terminates into s',\nWe then continue to follow the proof which uses the fact that the statement we need can only be construceted in one way, (more on that later)."},{"idx":60,"label":"20","overlay":5,"note":"due to the condition being true"},{"idx":61,"label":"20","overlay":6,"note":"We then get that the alternative construction if this stamtent must be that tthis stamtemnt holds true."},{"idx":62,"label":"20","overlay":7,"note":"But then we can use our induction hypotesis to prove our conclusin for this case. but we are not done yet..."},{"idx":63,"label":"20","overlay":8,"note":"As some of you might have noticed there is a trailing if_false case here, This is due to the fact that Lean can only see the if statment which can only be constructed using both of the if_true and if_false rules, we do not have te luxury of the side condition that the book uses here.\nWe must  instead tell lean  that if we  used  the false rule then the condition must have been true and false at the same time, and this leads to a controdiction,\nwhich then proves that this case is redundent and Lean becomes happy again."},{"idx":64,"label":"21","overlay":0,"note":"Last  exxample i have prepared for you to day is this beutiful proof.\nWhere the textbook uses the proof of \"Straightforward\" which the makers of lean have seemd to forget to implemnt.\n\nIn all reality there is no way to construct  a straight forward way, if you truly want to do this you would have to construct you own tactic called \"straightforward\", but even then it would not be able to solve all cases we would call straightforward, as there is no mathmatical structure which represent straightforwad."},{"idx":65,"label":"22","overlay":0,"note":"So in conclusion,\npen-and-papper proofs share a lot of similarities, making it a good mapping between them for these proofs, but..."},{"idx":66,"label":"22","overlay":1,"note":"how similar the proofs and constructions become deepnds on things such as notation which can be hard to get correct some times, and also the fact that some symbols are reseverd to Lean's internals forcing you to be creative to find similar symbols to use instead."},{"idx":67,"label":"22","overlay":2,"note":"Creating the types of the langugage seemd relative easy,  but...\n"},{"idx":68,"label":"22","overlay":3,"note":"Some types are harder to construct due to the book not giving a precisee definition to use."},{"idx":69,"label":"22","overlay":4,"note":"The ideas used throught the proofs such as induction,\nand matching on the possible ways to create a statment worked well. but..."},{"idx":70,"label":"22","overlay":5,"note":"Some cases are omitted as straightforward,\nSome are ignored due to side conditions."},{"idx":71,"label":"23","overlay":0,"note":"So for the first question regarding similatietes between the two,"},{"idx":72,"label":"23","overlay":1,"note":"I found that there is a high degree of similarities allowing for a good mapping from the text to Lean,\nbut there are some weakpoints where the mapping becomes weaker due to impresics definitions and over simplifications of some types, and parts of proofs.\n"},{"idx":73,"label":"23","overlay":2,"note":"For Rq2 which is inregard to assumptions made through out."},{"idx":74,"label":"23","overlay":3,"note":"There are some cases where the proofs are omitted leaving us with the assumption that\n1. it is true, and 2. that is easy, or straight forward to prove.\n\nIn lean this is not possible, as all cases needs to be evaluated, and wheter or not is straight forward is not something that lean can reason about."},{"idx":75,"label":"24","overlay":0,"note":"Thank you all for coming,"},{"idx":76,"label":"24","overlay":1,"note":"Any questions?"}]}